\chapter{Personal action}
\label{chap:personal_action}
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\epigraph{People donâ€™t spring into action just because they see smoke; 
they spring into action because they see others rushing in with water.}
{Leor Hackel and Gregg Sparkman} % on Slate.com Oct. 26, 2018.

This is the second of two chapters on actions to encourage sustainable 
living for individuals and society.
This chapter is a companion to 
Chapter~\ref{chap:government},
which focused on collective ways 
to achieve a sustainable society, 
often by changing the ``rules of the game.''
In contrast, 
this chapter (\ref{chap:personal_action}) focuses on individual actions
that can be taken 
within existing systems, structures, and political environments.
Individual actions are steps that can be taken %by individuals and families
to become more sustainable \emph{in spite of}
trends or incentives in broader society
that foster unsustainable practices or consumption.

This chapter answers the question 
``what can I do today to live a more sustainable life?''
% OR to contribute to a more sustainable society.
Again, like Chapter~\ref{chap:government}, 
there are many ways that individuals can take action
to become more sustainable. 
This chapter opens with stories of individuals striving to live
more sustainable lives. 
Thereafter, the chapter is structured similarly 
to Chapter~\ref{chap:government}
with \emph{sustainability sentences}, organized first by
the $PARC$ terms (Chapters~\ref{chap:population}--\ref{chap:impact_intensity})
of the IPARX equation (Equation~\ref{eq:IPARX})
and second by 
areas of life in which sustainability issues and choices emerge:
households, transportation, agriculture, and land use/urban planning 
(Chapters~\ref{chap:households}--\ref{chap:agriculture}).
The lists of possible personal actions are provided
mostly without comment.  
Readers are encouraged to explore the suggested actions that fit their
local situation, 
always keeping in mind the global perspective provided 
by Chapters~\ref{chap:introduction}--\ref{chap:impact_intensity}.
Questions and problems at the end of the chapter assist 
the exploration process.


%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\section{Stories of individual actions}
\label{sec:stories_individual_actions}
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%

From 2019--2021, 
Edgar McGregor picked up litter in the Angeles National Forest
in Southern California
for at least one
hour per day for 589 consecutive days~\cite{npr030821}. 
He earned more than \$400 (donated to charity) from recyclable materials he 
collected and, on at least one day, he filled a dumpster with a thousand pounds 
of trash. 
McGregor's actions illustrate that large, seemingly impossible tasks, like cleaning
a large (198 acres) public space from decades of litter, can be accomplished with dedication
and perseverance.
His documentation of progress on Twitter could be an example of the sustainability 
sentence: Individual + Education + Impact intensity. 
(See discussion question Q12.\ref{question:mcgregror} for further discussion.)

Wangari Maathai was a veterinary professor, author, 
member of the Kenyan parliament, founder of the Green Belt movement 
(see Question Q\ref{chap:land_use_urban_planning}.\ref{question:green_wall}),
and Nobel Peace Prize laureate.
She lived a fascinating, often turbulent, life.
Many ``sustainability sentences'' could describe her work;
Individual + Education + Land use is one good choice.
Her biography illustrates that bringing change, even positive change, often 
exacts a personal price. 
Those who want change must be willing to endure.

Joseph Lstiburek is the founding principal of Building Science Corporation and the
originator of the perfect wall concept.
Because his research and techniques have lead to building-code improvements that
save energy and prolong building life, his sustainability sentence could be
Individual + Research + Housing or Individual + Education + Housing.
Not all educators are teachers or professors and not all researchers work
for a university or tech start up. 

