Individuals have considerable choice of what to eat, where to obtain food, and
how to prepare food. 
This section presents two example ``sentences for sustainability'' related to 
food production and consumption.

\paragraph{Individual+Choices+Agriculture}
Probably the most important and high-impact activity an individual can take around
food is to reduce as much as possible the amount of food waste they generate.
Any wasted food embodies resources (such as energy) and emissions.
Individuals can adopt a climate-friendly or climate-friendlier diet, that is, to
improve the sustainability of \emph{what you eat}.
Typically these involve reductions to meat consumption, particularly beef.
There are a variety of ways to improve the sustainability of \emph{food production}.
Recall that what is least expensive is often the most environmentally friendly.
Cooking at home minimizes packaging and is usually the cheapest option (compared 
to say, buying prepared foods or eating at a restaurant).
Buy \emph{ingredients} (see Figure~\ref{fig:suburban_produce_aisle}), then 
\emph{make} food.
One step beyond that would be to raise your own food by gardening or harvest 
wild food, for instance by hunting, fishing, and/or gathering wild plants. 
One side benefit to such foraging is an investment in the state of the ecosystem.
A partial measure is buying direct from local farmers, perhaps at a farmers' 
market (see Figure~\ref{fig:urban_farmers_market}) or through community-supported 
agriculture.

\paragraph{Individual+Research+Agriculture}
The examples in the previous paragraph are based on general assumptions about what
is most likely to be sustainable behavior.
You could collect personal data to quantify what is most sustainable in your 
particular context or situation.
For example, perhaps you could develop a new meatless version of a favorite recipe.
Another example would be to collect data on what plants do best in your garden and
to record what inputs (water, fertilizer, your time) are required, which would
allow you to optimize your gardening for maximum sustainability impact.


